## Impacts of Climate Change on Antarctica

Antarctica, that vast, isolated continent of ice and existential dread, has not, to anyone's surprise, managed to escape the relentless creep of [warming](/Climate_change) and [ice loss](/Ice_loss) in recent decades. It seems even the planet's most formidable fortress against change is susceptible to the persistent assault of [greenhouse gas emissions](/Greenhouse_gas_emissions) from the rest of the world. &#91;1&#93; &#91;2&#93; The numbers, if you care for such tedious specifics, paint a rather clear picture: [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica) has endured a warming trend exceeding 0.1&#160;°C per decade, a steady climb from the 1950s through the 2000s. &#91;3&#93; Meanwhile, the more exposed and vulnerable [Antarctic Peninsula](/Antarctic_Peninsula) has already registered a staggering 3&#160;°C (5.4&#160;°F) increase since the middle of the 20th century, a testament to its direct confrontation with changing atmospheric and oceanic conditions. &#91;3&#93; Even the colder, historically more stable expanses of [East Antarctica](/East_Antarctica) managed to hold out, showing no significant warming until the early 2000s, a brief reprieve before the inevitable. &#91;4&#93; &#91;5&#93;

Surrounding this frozen landmass, the immense [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) has been performing a planetary service, absorbing more [oceanic heat](/Ocean_heat_content) than any other ocean basin on Earth. &#91;6&#93; This absorption isn't merely a surface phenomenon; strong warming has been observed at astonishing depths, reaching below 2,000&#160;m (6,600&#160;ft). &#91;7&#93; &#58;&#8202;1230&#8202; Specifically, the waters around [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica) have warmed by a full 1&#160;°C (1.8&#160;°F) since 1955, an unsettling indicator of profound changes at play. &#91;3&#93;

The consequences of this oceanic warming are, predictably, dire for the ice. The increased temperatures in the [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) have led to the pronounced weakening, and in some cases, outright collapse, of critical [ice shelves](/Ice_shelf). These floating extensions of land-based [glaciers](/Glacier) act as crucial buttresses, stabilizing the flow of ice from the continent into the sea. Their demise has allowed many coastal [glaciers](/Glacier) to accelerate their mass loss and retreat inland, contributing to a net [ice loss](/Ice_loss) across [Antarctica](/Antarctica) as a whole. &#91;7&#93; &#58;&#8202;1264&#8202; Though, in a minor counter-narrative, the inland regions of the [East Antarctic ice sheet](/East_Antarctic_ice_sheet) have continued to gain ice, a nuance that does little to offset the larger trend. By the turn of the next century, projections indicate that Antarctica's net [ice loss](/Ice_loss) will contribute approximately 11&#160;cm (5&#160;in) to global [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise). This, however, is merely the baseline. The more unsettling prospect of [Marine ice sheet instability](/Marine_ice_sheet_instability) looms, potentially adding tens of centimeters more if triggered before 2100. &#91;7&#93; &#58;&#8202;1270&#8202; Should warming continue unchecked, such instability becomes far more probable, with the potential to double the 21st-century global [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise), a truly inconvenient truth for coastal populations. &#91;8&#93; &#91;9&#93; &#91;10&#93;

Beyond the obvious melting, the influx of fresh [meltwater](/Meltwater) from the continent's retreating ice masses is actively diluting the saline [Antarctic bottom water](/Antarctic_bottom_water). &#91;11&#93; &#91;12&#93; This dilution, in turn, is weakening the lower cell of the [Southern Ocean overturning circulation](/Southern_Ocean_overturning_circulation) (SOOC), a fundamental component of global ocean currents. &#91;7&#93; &#58;&#8202;1240&#8202; Some research, with a delightful sense of impending doom, suggests a complete collapse of the SOOC could occur if global warming reaches between 1.7&#160;°C (3.1&#160;°F) and 3&#160;°C (5.4&#160;°F), though its full, devastating effects would unfold over multiple centuries. &#91;13&#93; These effects are not confined to the polar regions; they include a predicted decrease in precipitation across the [Southern Hemisphere](/Southern_Hemisphere) and a corresponding increase in the [Northern Hemisphere](/Northern_Hemisphere), an eventual collapse of [fisheries](/Fishery) in the [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean), and a potential [ecosystem collapse](/Ecosystem_collapse) for certain [marine ecosystems](/Marine_ecosystem). &#91;14&#93; While many Antarctic species remain blissfully undiscovered, existing data indicates increases in [Antarctic flora](/Antarctic_flora), &#91;15&#93; and larger [fauna](/Wildlife_of_Antarctica) such as [penguins](/Penguin) are already struggling to maintain suitable habitat. On the scarce ice-free land, thawing [permafrost](/Permafrost) releases both potent [greenhouse gases](/Greenhouse_gas) and previously frozen pollution, a testament to humanity's pervasive touch. &#91;16&#93; Furthermore, the warming of [Antarctica](/Antarctica) and the subsequent alterations in [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) circulation are not merely local phenomena; they ripple outwards, influencing climate patterns in parts of Africa, directly impacting regional rainfall and temperature variability. &#91;17&#93; &#91;18&#93;

The fate of the [West Antarctic ice sheet](/West_Antarctic_ice_sheet) appears sealed, likely destined for complete melting &#91;19&#93; &#91;20&#93; unless global temperatures are miraculously reduced by 2&#160;°C (3.6&#160;°F) below 2020 levels, a prospect as likely as finding a politician who genuinely cares. &#91;21&#93; The complete loss of this ice sheet is not a rapid event, but a drawn-out process, estimated to take anywhere between 500 and a staggering 13,000 years. &#91;22&#93; &#91;23&#93; Such a collapse would result in a global [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise) of 3.3&#160;m (10&#160;ft 10&#160;in), leaving only isolated ice caps on the highest mountains. If those stubborn ice caps also succumb, the rise would extend to 4.3&#160;m (14&#160;ft 1&#160;in). &#91;24&#93; In contrast, the much larger and more stable [East Antarctic ice sheet](/East_Antarctic_ice_sheet) is projected to contribute a comparatively modest 0.5&#160;m (1&#160;ft 8&#160;in) to 0.9&#160;m (2&#160;ft 11&#160;in) to [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise) under current warming scenarios, a mere fraction of the 53.3&#160;m (175&#160;ft) locked within its full extent. &#91;25&#93; However, should global warming reach around 3&#160;°C (5.4&#160;°F), vulnerable areas within [East Antarctica](/East_Antarctica) such as the [Wilkes Basin](/Wilkes_Basin) and [Aurora Basin](/Aurora_Basin) could collapse over approximately 2,000 years, &#91;22&#93; &#91;23&#93; potentially adding up to an additional 6.4&#160;m (21&#160;ft 0&#160;in) to global [sea levels](/Sea_level_rise). &#91;26&#93;

### Temperature and weather changes

One might assume [Antarctica](/Antarctica), being the coldest, driest, and highest continent on Earth, would be impervious to the whims of a changing climate. &#91;1&#93; Its inherent dryness means the air holds minimal water vapor, a poor conductor of heat. &#91;27&#93; The [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) surrounding it is remarkably efficient at absorbing heat, far more so than any other ocean. &#91;28&#93; The presence of vast, year-round [sea ice](/Sea_ice), with its high [albedo](/Albedo) (reflectivity), further augments the already dazzling white surface of the ice sheets, reflecting incoming solar radiation. &#91;1&#93;

Furthermore, [Antarctica's](/Antarctica) extreme cold fosters a unique atmospheric phenomenon: a regular [temperature inversion](/Temperature_inversion) every winter. Unlike elsewhere on Earth, where temperatures typically decrease with altitude, during the Antarctic winter, the surface of central [Antarctica](/Antarctica) becomes colder than the middle layers of the atmosphere. &#91;27&#93; This peculiar condition causes [greenhouse gases](/Greenhouse_gas) to trap heat within the middle atmosphere, ironically reducing its flow towards the surface and into space, rather than preventing heat from escaping the lower atmosphere as they do elsewhere. This effect persists until the Antarctic winter finally relents. &#91;27&#93; &#91;1&#93; Early [climate models](/Climate_model), perhaps overly optimistic, initially suggested that temperature trends over [Antarctica](/Antarctica) would manifest more gradually and subtly than in other regions of the globe. &#91;29&#93;

The historical record, however, has been notoriously sparse. For much of the 20th century, fewer than twenty permanent [weather stations](/Weather_station) dotted the continent, with a mere two venturing into its vast interior. [Automatic weather stations](/Automatic_weather_station) were deployed relatively late, providing only a brief observational record. Reliable [satellite temperature measurements](/Satellite_temperature_measurements) didn't even begin until 1981 and are inherently limited to cloud-free conditions. Consequently, comprehensive datasets representing the entire continent only began to emerge towards the very end of the 20th century. &#91;30&#93; &#91;failed verification&#93; The glaring exception was the [Antarctic Peninsula](/Antarctic_Peninsula), where warming was so pronounced and well-documented that it couldn't be ignored; &#91;31&#93; it was eventually confirmed to have warmed by a significant 3&#160;°C (5.4&#160;°F) since the mid-20th century. &#91;3&#93; Based on the limited data available at the time, several papers published in the early 2000s, including one notably led by [Peter Doran](/Peter_Doran) in 2002, claimed an overall cooling trend over continental [Antarctica](/Antarctica) outside the Peninsula. &#91;32&#93; &#91;33&#93; Doran's analysis, in particular, indicated stronger cooling than warming between 1966 and 2000, specifically highlighting the [McMurdo Dry Valleys](/McMurdo_Dry_Valleys) in [East Antarctica](/East_Antarctica) as having experienced a cooling of 0.7&#160;°C per decade. &#91;34&#93; Even then, the paper cautiously acknowledged its data limitations and still identified warming over 42% of the continent. &#91;34&#93; &#91;35&#93;

Despite these caveats, the paper garnered widespread media attention, with numerous journalists seizing upon its findings as "contradictory" to the notion of global warming. &#91;37&#93; &#91;38&#93; &#91;39&#93; This narrative, predictably, drew sharp criticism from the scientific community at the time. &#91;40&#93; &#91;41&#93; The manufactured "controversy" surrounding Antarctic cooling gained further, and frankly, ridiculous, traction in 2004 when [Michael Crichton](/Michael_Crichton) incorporated it into his novel, [State of Fear](/State_of_Fear). The book, a fictional tale of climate scientists conspiring to fabricate evidence of global warming, audaciously cited Doran's study as "proof" that warming was confined solely to the [Antarctic Peninsula](/Antarctic_Peninsula). &#91;42&#93; This novel was even invoked in a 2006 [US Senate](/US_Senate) hearing, lending spurious support to [climate change denial](/Climate_change_denial). &#91;43&#93; In response, [Peter Doran](/Peter_Doran) himself was compelled to publish a statement in [The New York Times](/The_New_York_Times), decrying the blatant misinterpretation of his work. &#91;35&#93; Both the [British Antarctic Survey](/British_Antarctic_Survey) and [NASA](/NASA) also issued statements reaffirming the robustness of climate science in the wake of the hearing. &#91;44&#93; &#91;45&#93;

By 2009, researchers had painstakingly combined historical [weather-station](/Weather_station) data with modern [satellite measurements](/Satellite_temperature_measurements) to construct consistent temperature records extending back to 1957. These revised records unequivocally demonstrated a continent-wide warming trend of greater than 0.05&#160;°C per decade. Crucially, the earlier perceived cooling in [East Antarctica](/East_Antarctica) was revealed to be more than offset by a significant average temperature increase of at least 0.176 ± 0.06&#160;°C per decade in [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica). &#91;36&#93; This pivotal paper was widely reported, &#91;46&#93; &#91;47&#93; and subsequent research only served to confirm the clear warming trend over [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica) throughout the 20th century, with the only remaining uncertainty being the precise magnitude of the warming. &#91;48&#93; During 2012–2013, estimates derived from [WAIS Divide](/WAIS_Divide_ice_core) [ice cores](/Ice_core) and updated temperature records from [Byrd Station](/Byrd_Station) suggested an even more substantial warming in [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica) of 2.4&#160;°C (4.3&#160;°F) since 1958, translating to approximately 0.46&#160;°C (0.83&#160;°F) per decade. &#91;49&#93; &#91;50&#93; &#91;51&#93; &#91;52&#93; However, some scientists, ever cautious, continued to emphasize the inherent uncertainties in these figures. &#91;53&#93; A definitive study in 2022 further refined the warming of the central area of the [West Antarctic Ice Sheet](/West_Antarctic_Ice_Sheet) between 1959 and 2000 to 0.31&#160;°C (0.56&#160;°F) per decade and, with chilling certainty, attributed it to the increases in [greenhouse gas](/Greenhouse_gas) concentrations resulting from human activity. &#91;54&#93; Similarly, the strong cooling previously observed at [McMurdo Dry Valleys](/McMurdo_Dry_Valleys) was confirmed as a localized trend, not indicative of the broader continental picture. &#91;55&#93;

The [Antarctica-wide](/Antarctica) warming trend, far from abating, continued its upward trajectory after 2000. In February 2020, the continent shattered its own record, registering an astonishing 18.3&#160;°C, surpassing the previous high of 17.5&#160;°C set in March 2015. &#91;56&#93; Even the interior of [East Antarctica](/East_Antarctica), once thought immune, displayed clear warming between 2000 and 2020. &#91;5&#93; &#91;57&#93; Most strikingly, the [South Pole](/South_Pole) itself warmed by an alarming 0.61 ± 0.34&#160;°C per decade between 1990 and 2020, a rate three times the global average. &#91;4&#93; &#91;58&#93; Conversely, shifts in large-scale atmospheric circulation patterns, such as the [Interdecadal Pacific Oscillation](/Interdecadal_Pacific_Oscillation) (IPO) and the [Southern Annular Mode](/Southern_Annular_Mode) (SAM), have temporarily slowed or partially reversed the warming in [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica), with the [Antarctic Peninsula](/Antarctic_Peninsula) even experiencing a period of cooling since 2002. &#91;59&#93; &#91;60&#93; &#91;61&#93; While variability in these patterns is a natural component of the climate system, historical [ozone depletion](/Ozone_depletion) had previously caused the SAM to become unusually strong, a strength unprecedented in 600 years of observations. Studies initiated around 2002 correctly predicted a reversal in the SAM as the [ozone layer](/Ozone_layer) began its slow recovery following the implementation of the [Montreal Protocol](/Montreal_Protocol), &#91;62&#93; &#91;63&#93; &#91;64&#93; and these observed changes are consistent with those scientific forecasts. &#91;65&#93;

Under the most aggressive [climate change scenario](/Climate_change_scenario), designated as [RCP8.5](/Representative_Concentration_Pathway), predictive models ominously suggest Antarctic surface temperatures could soar by 3&#160;°C (5.4&#160;°F) by 2070, &#91;66&#93; and by an average of 4&#160;°C (7.2&#160;°F) by 2100. This drastic warming would be accompanied by a 30% increase in precipitation and a 30% decrease in [sea ice](/Sea_ice) by the end of the century. &#91;67&#93; The [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) waters south of [50°&#160;S latitude](/50th_parallel_south) would also face significant warming, projected to increase by approximately 1.9&#160;°C (3.4&#160;°F) by 2070. &#91;66&#93; It's worth noting, with a weary sigh, that while RCPs were developed in the late 2000s, more recent research from the early 2020s considers RCP8.5 to be far less likely &#91;68&#93; than more moderate scenarios like RCP 4.5, which represent a middle ground between the worst-case outcomes and the ambitious goals of the [Paris Agreement](/Paris_Agreement). &#91;69&#93; &#91;70&#93; Should a low-emission scenario, largely consistent with the [Paris Agreement](/Paris_Agreement) targets, be diligently followed, [Antarctica](/Antarctica) would experience a much more constrained surface and ocean warming of less than 1&#160;°C (1.8&#160;°F) by 2070. In this relatively optimistic, yet still challenging, future, less than 15% of [sea ice](/Sea_ice) would be lost, and precipitation would increase by less than 10%. &#91;66&#93; A small comfort, perhaps, but a comfort nonetheless.

### Effects on ocean currents

• [Main article: Southern Ocean overturning circulation](/Southern_Ocean_overturning_circulation)
• [See also: Effects of climate change on oceans](/Effects_of_climate_change_on_oceans)

Between 1971 and 2018, a staggering 90% of the [thermal energy](/Thermal_energy) generated by [global heating](/Earth%27s_Energy_Imbalance) was absorbed by the world's oceans. &#91;72&#93; Among them, the [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) stands out as the most prodigious heat absorber; after 2005, it accounted for an astonishing 67% to 98% of all heat entering the oceans. &#91;28&#93; The temperature of the ocean's upper layer in [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica) has already risen by 1&#160;°C (1.8&#160;°F) since 1955, and the powerful [Antarctic Circumpolar Current](/Antarctic_Circumpolar_Current) (ACC) is warming at a rate exceeding the global average. &#91;3&#93; Furthermore, this vast oceanic expanse serves as an immensely important [carbon sink](/Carbon_sink), diligently pulling [carbon dioxide](/Carbon_dioxide) from the atmosphere. &#91;73&#93; &#91;74&#93; These critical properties are intricately linked to the [Southern Ocean overturning circulation](/Southern_Ocean_overturning_circulation) (SOOC), which forms one half of the global [thermohaline circulation](/Thermohaline_circulation). Consequently, projections for when global warming will inevitably reach 2&#160;°C (3.6&#160;°F) – a threshold that appears unavoidable in any scenario without drastic reductions in [greenhouse gas emissions](/Greenhouse_gas_emissions) – are more dependent on the strength of this circulation than almost any other factor, save for the emissions themselves. &#91;13&#93;

The [overturning circulation](/Southern_Ocean_overturning_circulation) itself comprises two distinct parts: a smaller upper cell, primarily influenced by winds and precipitation, and a larger, deeper lower cell, whose characteristics are defined by the temperature and salinity of the frigid [Antarctic bottom water](/Antarctic_bottom_water). &#91;76&#93; Since the 1970s, observations have indicated a strengthening of the upper cell by 50–60%, while, rather ominously, the lower cell has weakened by 10–20%. &#91;77&#93; &#91;75&#93; While the natural cycle of the [Interdecadal Pacific Oscillation](/Interdecadal_Pacific_Oscillation) (IPO) has contributed to some of these shifts, [climate change](/Climate_change) has played an undeniable role &#91;78&#93; &#91;79&#93; by altering the pattern of the [Southern Annular Mode](/Southern_Annular_Mode) (SAM), which in turn modifies regional winds and precipitation. &#91;28&#93;

A significant and concerning factor is the influx of fresh [meltwater](/Meltwater) from the eroding [West Antarctic ice sheet](/West_Antarctic_ice_sheet), which dilutes the naturally more saline [Antarctic bottom water](/Antarctic_bottom_water). &#91;11&#93; &#91;12&#93; This bottom water, a dense, cold mass, flows at an immense rate of 1100–1500 billion tons (GT) per year. &#91;7&#93; &#58;&#8202;1240&#8202; Interestingly, a temporary reduction in [ice-shelf](/Ice_shelf) melting in [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica) during the 2010s allowed for a partial, fleeting recovery of the [Antarctic bottom water](/Antarctic_bottom_water) and, consequently, the lower cell of the circulation. &#91;80&#93; However, the prevailing expectation, given current trends, is for greater melting and a continued decline of this vital circulation in the future. &#91;81&#93;

As the [bottom water](/Antarctic_bottom_water) weakens and the flow of warmer, fresher waters intensifies near the surface, the upper layers of the ocean become more buoyant. This buoyancy makes them less likely to sink and mix with the colder, deeper layers, a process that leads to increased [ocean stratification](/Ocean_stratification). &#91;82&#93; &#91;77&#93; &#91;75&#93; One particular study suggests that the strength of the [circulation](/Southern_Ocean_overturning_circulation) could be halved by 2050 under the most extreme, though now considered less likely, [climate-change scenario](/Climate_change_scenario), with even greater losses projected thereafter. &#91;81&#93; &#91;14&#93; [Paleoclimate](/Paleoclimate) evidence reveals that the entire circulation has experienced significant weakening or even complete collapse in the distant past. Preliminary research, with a hint of foreboding, suggests such a collapse may become likely once global warming reaches between 1.7&#160;°C (3.1&#160;°F) and 3&#160;°C (5.4&#160;°F). However, this estimate is acknowledged to be considerably less certain than those for the majority of other [tipping points in the climate system](/Tipping_points_in_the_climate_system). &#91;13&#93; Should such a collapse occur, it would be a prolonged event, with one estimate placing its full unfolding sometime before 2300, rather than within this century. &#91;83&#93; Much like the more extensively studied [Atlantic meridional overturning circulation](/Atlantic_meridional_overturning_circulation) (AMOC), a major slowing or collapse of the SOOC would unleash substantial regional and global effects. &#91;13&#93; Some of the likely consequences include a notable decline in precipitation in [Southern Hemisphere](/Southern_Hemisphere) nations such as [Australia](/Australia), a corresponding increase in precipitation in the [Northern Hemisphere](/Northern_Hemisphere), and an eventual decline of [fisheries](/Fishery) in the [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean), which could, in turn, lead to a potential collapse of some crucial [marine ecosystems](/Marine_ecosystem). &#91;14&#93; While these effects are expected to manifest over centuries, &#91;14&#93; research into their specifics remains limited, and many details are, unfortunately, still unknown. &#91;13&#93;

### Impacts on Africa

The remote changes occurring in Antarctic ice and the intricate dance of [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) circulation are not confined to the polar reaches; they exert a significant influence on global climate patterns, including the critical elements of rainfall and temperature variability across the African continent. Antarctic warming directly impacts the powerful [Antarctic Circumpolar Current](/Antarctic_Circumpolar_Current) and the [Agulhas Current](/Agulhas_Current), which serve as vital conduits for transporting heat and moisture across the [Southern Hemisphere](/Southern_Hemisphere). &#91;84&#93; &#91;85&#93; The regional effects of these teleconnections are, predictably, varied and complex: northern Africa faces an exacerbation of existing water scarcity issues; East Africa is grappling with highly erratic rainfall patterns, oscillating between devastating droughts and intense, destructive downpours; and southern Africa is confronting a grim reality of rising temperatures, unpredictable flooding, and prolonged periods of drought. &#91;86&#93; &#91;87&#93; Recognizing the profound implications, scientific programs, such as South Africa's [South African National Antarctic Programme](/South_African_National_Antarctic_Programme), are diligently monitoring Antarctic climate processes and their downstream impacts. This research is crucial in supporting regional climate adaptation strategies across Africa, though one wonders if adaptation can truly keep pace with such fundamental shifts. &#91;88&#93; &#91;89&#93;

### Effects on the cryosphere

#### Observed changes in ice mass

The contrasting temperature trends across different parts of [Antarctica](/Antarctica) create a rather inconvenient truth: some locations, particularly along the coasts, are experiencing significant mass loss, while areas further inland continue to gain mass. This regional dichotomy, coupled with the sheer remoteness of the continent, makes the task of accurately estimating an average trend for the entire ice sheet a formidable challenge. &#91;90&#93;

In 2018, a comprehensive, systematic review of all available studies and data, conducted by the [Ice Sheet Mass Balance Inter-comparison Exercise](/Ice_Sheet_Mass_Balance_Inter-comparison_Exercise) (IMBIE), provided a clearer, albeit still concerning, picture. The review estimated that the [West Antarctic ice sheet](/West_Antarctic_ice_sheet) saw an increase in mass loss, accelerating from 53 ± 29 Gt (gigatonnes) per year in 1992 to a substantial 159 ± 26 Gt per year in the final five years of the study period. On the [Antarctic Peninsula](/Antarctic_Peninsula), the study projected an annual loss of 20 ± 15 Gt, with this rate of loss increasing by approximately 15 Gt per year after 2000. A significant portion of this accelerated loss was attributed to the disintegration of vital [ice shelves](/Ice_shelf) that buttress the glaciers. &#91;91&#93; The IMBIE review's overarching conclusion was that [Antarctica](/Antarctica) collectively lost an astonishing 2,720 ± 1,390 gigatons of ice between 1992 and 2017, averaging 109 ± 56 Gt per year. This colossal loss directly translated to a contribution of 7.6&#160;mm (0.30&#160;in) to global [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise). &#91;91&#93;

However, a 2021 analysis, drawing upon data from four distinct research satellite systems ([Envisat](/Envisat), [European Remote-Sensing Satellite](/European_Remote-Sensing_Satellite), [GRACE and GRACE-FO](/GRACE_and_GRACE-FO), and [ICESat](/ICESat)), presented a slightly different perspective. This analysis indicated an annual mass loss of approximately 12 Gt from 2012 to 2016. This seemingly lower figure was attributed to a much greater ice gain in [East Antarctica](/East_Antarctica) than had been previously estimated, which, to some extent, offset most of the losses observed from [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica). &#91;92&#93;

The ability of the [East Antarctic ice sheet](/East_Antarctic_ice_sheet) to actually *gain* mass despite continental warming is a fascinating, if not entirely reassuring, phenomenon. This occurs because the [effects of climate change on the water cycle](/Effects_of_climate_change_on_the_water_cycle) are increasing precipitation over its vast surface. This additional precipitation, falling as snow, then freezes and contributes to the accretion of more ice, a cold comfort in the face of overall decline. &#91;7&#93; &#58;&#8202;1262&#8202; A study published in 2023 further complicated the narrative, reporting that the total area of Antarctic [ice shelves](/Ice_shelves) actually increased by approximately 5,305&#160;km² (about 0.4%) between 2009 and 2019. This net increase was a result of the growth of the largest [ice shelves](/Ice_shelves) in [East Antarctica](/East_Antarctica) outweighing concurrent losses from [ice shelves](/Ice_shelves) in [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica) and the [Antarctic Peninsula](/Antarctic_Peninsula). &#91;93&#93; It is crucial, however, to understand that these slight net increases in isolated years or the growth of specific [ice shelves](/Ice_shelves) do not in any way contradict the overwhelming and decades-long net decrease that the Antarctic [sea ice](/Antarctic_sea_ice) has undergone. To suggest otherwise would be a disservice to the facts. &#91;94&#93; &#91;95&#93; &#91;96&#93; &#91;97&#93;

#### Black carbon pollution

[Black carbon](/Black_carbon), the sooty byproduct of incomplete [fuel combustion](/Internal_combustion_engine), is not content to remain localized. It travels vast distances, carried by atmospheric currents, and eventually finds its way to the pristine expanses of [Antarctica](/Antarctica). Once there, this dark particulate matter accumulates on the snow and ice, dramatically reducing its natural reflectivity (its [albedo](/Albedo)). This reduction means the surface absorbs more solar energy, &#91;98&#93; accelerating melting and potentially creating a vicious [ice-albedo feedback](/Ice-albedo_feedback) loop where the resulting [meltwater](/Meltwater), being darker, absorbs even more heat from sunlight, thus melting more ice. &#91;99&#93; Due to its extreme remoteness, [Antarctica](/Antarctica) has historically boasted the cleanest snow on the planet. According to some research, the current effects of [black carbon](/Black_carbon) across the vast majority of [West](/West_Antarctica) and [East Antarctica](/East_Antarctica) are still minimal, with one 47-year [ice core](/Ice_core) revealing an [albedo](/Albedo) reduction of only about 0.5%. &#91;100&#93; &#91;101&#93;

However, human activity, even in this remote wilderness, leaves its mark. The highest concentrations of [black carbon](/Black_carbon) are predictably found on the [Antarctic Peninsula](/Antarctic_Peninsula), an area with a higher density of human presence compared to other regions. &#91;102&#93; &#91;98&#93; Deposits of [black carbon](/Black_carbon) near frequently visited tourist sites and active research stations have been shown to increase summer seasonal melting by an estimated 5 to 23&#160;kg (11 to 51&#160;lb) of snow per square meter, a tangible and localized impact on the delicate environment. &#91;98&#93;

#### 21st-century ice loss and sea level rise

By the year 2100, the net [ice loss](/Ice_loss) from [Antarctica](/Antarctica) is projected to contribute approximately 11&#160;cm (4.3&#160;in) to the global [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise). &#91;7&#93; &#58;&#8202;1270&#8202; However, this figure represents merely the most straightforward, linear projection. Other, more unsettling processes have the potential to significantly amplify [West Antarctica's](/West_Antarctica) contribution to rising [sea levels](/Sea_level_rise). One such mechanism is [Marine ice sheet instability](/Marine_ice_sheet_instability), a phenomenon where warm ocean currents can penetrate beneath the ice sheet, separating it from the [seafloor](/Seafloor) once the ice mass is no longer sufficiently heavy to displace these intrusions. &#91;104&#93; Another, even more dramatic, concept is marine ice cliff instability. This theory posits that ice cliffs exceeding 100&#160;m (330&#160;ft) in height could spontaneously collapse under their own immense weight once they are no longer supported, or "buttressed," by adjacent [ice shelves](/Ice_shelf). While this process has never been directly observed and is currently only a feature of certain models, its implications are profound. &#91;105&#93; By 2100, these combined processes could inflate the [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise) attributable to [Antarctica](/Antarctica) to a grim 41&#160;cm (16&#160;in) under a low-emission scenario, and a truly alarming 57&#160;cm (22&#160;in) under a high-emission scenario. &#91;7&#93; &#58;&#8202;1270&#8202;

Some scientists, with a perhaps more realistic view of humanity's trajectory, have offered even higher estimates. All, however, agree that melting in [Antarctica](/Antarctica) would have a far greater impact and become much more probable under higher-warming scenarios, potentially doubling the overall 21st-century [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise) to 2&#160;m (7&#160;ft) or even more. &#91;8&#93; &#91;9&#93; &#91;10&#93; According to one particularly sobering study, if the [Paris Agreement](/Paris_Agreement) goals are met and global warming is successfully limited to 2&#160;°C (3.6&#160;°F), the current rate of [ice loss](/Ice_loss) in [Antarctica](/Antarctica) will persist for the remainder of the 21st century. However, if the world follows a trajectory leading to 3&#160;°C (5.4&#160;°F) of warming, Antarctic [ice loss](/Ice_loss) is projected to accelerate dramatically after 2060, eventually contributing an additional 0.5&#160;cm (0.20&#160;in) per year to global [sea levels](/Sea_level_rise) by 2100. &#91;106&#93;

#### Long-term sea level rise

The grim reality is that [sea levels](/Sea_level_rise) will continue their inexorable ascent long after 2100, though the rate of this rise could vary wildly depending on the choices made today. According to the most recent, and highly authoritative, reports from the [Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change](/Intergovernmental_Panel_on_Climate_Change) ([SROCC](/SROCC) and the [IPCC Sixth Assessment Report](/IPCC_Sixth_Assessment_Report)), even under a low-emission scenario, we are looking at a median rise of 16&#160;cm (6.3&#160;in) with a maximum of 37&#160;cm (15&#160;in). The highest-emission scenario, a future we are ostensibly trying to avoid, paints a far more catastrophic picture: a median rise of 1.46&#160;m (5&#160;ft), with a minimum of 60&#160;cm (2&#160;ft) and a staggering maximum of 2.89&#160;m (9&#160;ft 6&#160;in). &#91;7&#93;

Over these longer, multi-century timescales, the [West Antarctic ice sheet](/West_Antarctic_ice_sheet) emerges as an area of extreme vulnerability. Though significantly smaller than its eastern counterpart, it is largely grounded deep below [sea level](/Sea_level_rise), making it intrinsically unstable. The complete melting of all the ice contained within [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica) would unleash a colossal 4.3&#160;m (14&#160;ft 1&#160;in) of global [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise). &#91;24&#93; While isolated mountain ice caps, not in direct contact with warming ocean waters, are somewhat less vulnerable, the vast majority of the ice sheet lies precariously submerged. The collapse of the [West Antarctic ice sheet](/West_Antarctic_ice_sheet) alone would contribute approximately 3.3&#160;m (10&#160;ft 10&#160;in) to global [sea levels](/Sea_level_rise). &#91;108&#93; This type of collapse is now considered almost inevitable, a chilling echo of history. Evidence suggests a similar event occurred during the [Eemian](/Eemian) period 125,000 years ago, when global temperatures were strikingly similar to those experienced in the early 21st century. &#91;109&#93; &#91;110&#93; &#91;19&#93; Furthermore, the [Amundsen Sea](/Amundsen_Sea), which directly interfaces with critical parts of the [West Antarctic ice sheet](/West_Antarctic_ice_sheet), appears to be warming at rates that, if sustained, make the ice sheet's eventual collapse unavoidable. &#91;20&#93; &#91;111&#93;

The only conceivable way to reverse the [ice loss](/Ice_loss) from [West Antarctica](/West_Antarctica), once it has been irrevocably triggered, would be to reduce the global temperature to 1&#160;°C (1.8&#160;°F) below pre-industrial levels, effectively a 2&#160;°C (3.6&#160;°F) reduction below 2020 temperatures. &#91;21&#93; This is, of course, a monumental task bordering on the fantastical. Other researchers have floated the idea of a [climate engineering](/Climate_engineering) intervention, perhaps deploying seabed-anchored curtains to stabilize the ice sheet's [glaciers](/Glacier). Such a proposal might delay its loss by centuries, theoretically granting the environment more time to adapt. However, this remains a highly uncertain proposition and would undoubtedly rank among the most expensive and ambitious engineering projects ever attempted. &#91;112&#93; &#91;113&#93; Without such drastic, unprecedented measures, the complete disappearance of the [West Antarctic ice sheet](/West_Antarctic_ice_sheet) is estimated to unfold over approximately 2,000 years, though the total loss of West Antarctic ice could take anywhere from at least 500 years to possibly as long as 13,000 years. &#91;22&#93; &#91;23&#93; Once the ice sheet is gone, the subsequent [isostatic rebound](/Isostatic_rebound) of the land, relieved of its immense ice burden, would result in an additional 1&#160;m (3&#160;ft 3&#160;in) of [sea level rise](/Sea_level_rise) over the following 1,000 years, a final, lingering consequence. &#91;26&#93;

In stark contrast to its western counterpart, the [East Antarctic ice sheet](/East_Antarctic_ice_sheet) is considerably more stable. Its complete loss would necessitate global warming of between 5&#160;°C (9.0&#160;°F) and 10&#160;°C (18&#160;°F), and would unfold over a minimum of 10,000 years. &#91;22&#93; &#91;23&#93; However, even within this colossal, more resilient ice sheet, certain regions are perilously vulnerable. Parts such as the [Totten Glacier](/Totten_Glacier) and the [Wilkes Basin](/Wilkes_Basin) are situated in vulnerable [subglacial basins](/Subglacial_basin) that lie below [sea level](/Sea_level_rise). Estimates suggest that the irreversible loss of these basins could begin once global warming reaches 3&#160;°C (5.4&#160;°F), though the critical threshold for irreversibility may fall anywhere between 2&#160;°C (3.6&#160;°F) and 6&#160;°C (11&#160;°F). Once global warming surpasses this critical point for the collapse of these [subglacial basins](/Subglacial_basin), their loss is likely to occur over approximately 2,000 years, though it could be as rapid as 500 years or as protracted as 10,000 years. &#91;22&#93; &#91;23&#93;

The complete loss of all the ice from these vulnerable East Antarctic basins would add a substantial 1.4&#160;m (4&#160;ft 7&#160;in) to 6.4&#160;m (21&#160;ft 0&#160;in) to global [sea levels](/Sea_level_rise), depending on the specific [ice sheet model](/Ice_sheet_model) employed for the calculation. The subsequent [isostatic rebound](/Isostatic_rebound) of the newly ice-free land would contribute an additional 8&#160;cm (3.1&#160;in) to 57&#160;cm (1&#160;ft 10&#160;in). &#91;26&#93; Historical evidence from the [Pleistocene](/Pleistocene) epoch demonstrates that partial loss from these regions can indeed occur at lower warming levels. The [Wilkes Basin](/Wilkes_Basin), for instance, is estimated to have lost enough ice to contribute 0.5&#160;m (1&#160;ft 8&#160;in) to [sea levels](/Sea_level_rise) between 115,000 and 129,000 years ago during the [Eemian](/Eemian), and approximately 0.9&#160;m (2&#160;ft 11&#160;in) between 318,000 and 339,000 years ago during [Marine Isotope Stage 9](/Marine_Isotope_Stage_9). &#91;25&#93; History, it seems, has a habit of repeating itself, albeit with higher stakes this time.

### Permafrost thaw

While [Antarctica](/Antarctica) possesses significantly less [permafrost](/Permafrost) than its northern counterpart, the [Arctic](/Arctic), &#91;69&#93; the warming trends are, predictably, impacting what little it does have. Like in the Arctic, warming temperatures are causing Antarctic [permafrost](/Permafrost) to thaw. This thawing leads to increased erosion of the fragile soil and, inevitably, reshapes the distribution of plant life across the affected landscapes. &#91;114&#93;

The [permafrost](/Permafrost) in [Antarctica](/Antarctica) acts as a cold storage unit, trapping a variety of compounds that are anything but benign. These include [persistent organic pollutants](/Persistent_organic_pollutant) (POPs) such as [polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons](/Polycyclic_aromatic_hydrocarbon), many of which are known carcinogens or can cause severe liver damage. &#91;115&#93; Also entombed are [polychlorinated biphenyls](/Polychlorinated_biphenyl) (PCBs) like [hexachlorobenzene](/Hexachlorobenzene) (HCB) and the infamous [DDT](/DDT), both associated with decreased reproductive success and various immunohematological disorders. &#91;116&#93; Beyond these organic horrors, Antarctic soils also harbor heavy metals, including [mercury](/Mercury_(element)), [lead](/Lead), and [cadmium](/Cadmium), all of which are capable of causing [endocrine disruption](/Endocrine_disruption), [DNA](/DNA) damage, [immunotoxicity](/Immunotoxicity), and reproductive toxicity. &#91;117&#93; As the contaminated [permafrost](/Permafrost) thaws, these noxious compounds are released, altering the chemistry of surface water and, through processes of [bioaccumulation](/Bioaccumulation) and [biomagnification](/Biomagnification), spreading throughout the delicate [food web](/Food_web). &#91;16&#93; While [permafrost](/Permafrost) thaw does also result in [greenhouse gas emissions](/Greenhouse_gas_emissions), the limited volume of Antarctic [permafrost](/Permafrost) relative to the vast Arctic expanses means that it is not currently considered a significant driver of global [climate change](/Climate_change). &#91;69&#93; A small mercy, perhaps, in a sea of problems.

### Ecological effects

• [See also: Wildlife of Antarctica](/Wildlife_of_Antarctica)

#### Marine ecosystems

The vast majority of species inhabiting [Antarctica](/Antarctica) are, unsurprisingly, marine. By 2015, a mere 57 of the 8,354 taxonomically accepted species discovered in [Antarctica](/Antarctica) were not marine, a testament to the dominance of the ocean. &#91;118&#93; And yet, this is likely just the tip of the iceberg; [Antarctica](/Antarctica) may harbor up to 17,000 species. &#91;119&#93; The irony is that while 90% of the ocean surrounding [Antarctica](/Antarctica) plunges to depths greater than 1,000&#160;m (3,281&#160;ft), only a paltry 30% of [benthic-sample](/Benthic_zone) locations have been taken at these profound depths, leaving much of its biodiversity a mystery. &#91;120&#93; On the Antarctic [continental shelves](/Continental_shelf), warming ocean waters are likely to cause an increase in [benthic-zone](/Benthic_zone) biomass, primarily benefiting species like [seaweed](/Seaweed). However, this growth comes at a cost, as an estimated 12% of native [benthic species](/Benthic_zone) may be outcompeted and driven to extinction. &#91;121&#93; &#58;&#8202;2327&#8202; These are, of course, preliminary estimates; the true vulnerabilities of most Antarctic species remain largely unassessed. &#91;122&#93;

Unlike the [Arctic](/Arctic), observed changes in [marine primary production](/Marine_primary_production) across the [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) have been relatively minimal thus far. &#91;121&#93; &#58;&#8202;2327&#8202; However, projections suggest that an increase in [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) primary production could occur after 2100. This increase, if it materializes, would have a cascading effect, blocking many essential nutrients from reaching other oceans and leading to a corresponding decrease in production elsewhere, a delightful ripple effect of human interference. &#91;121&#93; &#58;&#8202;2329&#8202; Some microbial communities have already shown negative responses to [ocean acidification](/Ocean_acidification), and there is a very real risk that future acidification will threaten the delicate eggs of [pteropods](/Pteropod), a crucial type of [zooplankton](/Zooplankton). &#91;121&#93; &#58;&#8202;2327&#8202;

[Antarctic krill](/Antarctic_krill) (*Euphasia superba*) are a cornerstone species, the very lynchpin of the Antarctic [food web](/Food_web). They graze on phytoplankton and, in turn, serve as the primary food source for fish and [penguins](/Penguin) alike. &#91;124&#93; Disturbingly, krill populations appear to have been in decline in parts of the Southwest [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) since the 1970s. &#91;123&#93; Looking ahead, [Antarctic krill](/Antarctic_krill) are projected to abandon the fastest-warming areas, such as the [Weddell Sea](/Weddell_Sea), while [icefish](/Channichthyidae) may find the shelf waters around Antarctic islands increasingly unsuitable for their survival. &#91;121&#93; &#58;&#8202;2327&#8202; Species like [salps](/Salp), with their more adaptable nature, are likely to move in and replace the krill in the areas they vacate, fundamentally altering the [ecosystem](/Ecosystem). &#91;66&#93;

The observed shifts and decreases in krill and [copepod](/Copepod) numbers are already impeding the recovery of [baleen whale](/Baleen_whale) populations, which are still struggling to rebound from the devastating declines caused by historical [whaling](/Whaling). Without a reversal in rising temperatures, [baleen whales](/Baleen_whale) will likely be forced to alter their migratory patterns or face the very real threat of local extinction. &#91;125&#93; Many other marine species are expected to migrate into Antarctic waters as the oceans continue to warm, creating intense competition with native species. &#91;126&#93; Some research grimly suggests that at 3&#160;°C (5.4&#160;°F) of warming, the diversity of Antarctic species would plummet by nearly 17%, and their suitable climate area would shrink by a devastating 50%. &#91;127&#93; Overall, the value of the region's [fisheries](/Fishery) may decline significantly under scenarios of high warming. &#91;66&#93;

#### Penguins

[Penguins](/Penguin), those iconic, somewhat absurd inhabitants of the frozen south, sit at the apex of the [Antarctic food web](/Antarctic_food_web) and are already experiencing substantial impacts from [climate change](/Climate_change). Populations of [Adélie penguins](/Ad%C3%A9lie_penguin), [chinstrap penguins](/Chinstrap_penguin), [emperor penguin](/Emperor_penguin), and [king penguins](/King_penguin) have been observed in decline, a stark indicator of the changes sweeping through their habitat. &#91;121&#93; &#58;&#8202;2327&#8202; In a twist of ecological irony, the numbers of [gentoo penguins](/Gentoo_penguin) have actually increased. &#91;121&#93; &#58;&#8202;2327&#8202; These opportunistic birds, being ice-intolerant and utilizing mosses for nesting, have spread into previously inaccessible territories, thriving in the newly exposed, ice-free areas. &#91;128&#93; The more vulnerable penguin species can respond to these pressures through [acclimatization](/Acclimatization) (adjusting to new conditions), [adaptation](/Adaptation) (evolving over generations), or, more often, through range shift, which typically leads to local extinction as they attempt to colonize new areas. &#91;129&#93; &#91;130&#93;

As far back as 2008, it was estimated that every 0.26&#160;°C (0.47&#160;°F) increase in [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) temperature reduced [king penguin](/King_penguin) populations by nine percent. &#91;131&#93; Under the worst-case warming scenario, [king penguins](/King_penguin) are projected to permanently lose at least two of their current eight breeding sites, forcing a staggering 70% of the species (1.1 million pairs) to relocate to avoid extinction. &#91;132&#93; &#91;133&#93; [Emperor penguin](/Emperor_penguin) populations face a similarly dire future; without significant [climate mitigation](/Climate_change_mitigation), 80% of their populations are at risk of extinction by 2100. Should the world adhere to the [Paris Agreement](/Paris_Agreement) temperature goals, this number could fall to 31% under the 2&#160;°C (3.6&#160;°F) goal, and to a slightly less catastrophic 19% under the 1.5&#160;°C (2.7&#160;°F) goal. &#91;134&#93;

A 27-year study, published in 2014, on the largest colony of [Magellanic penguins](/Magellanic_penguin) revealed that extreme weather events, exacerbated by [climate change](/Climate_change), kill an average of seven percent of penguin chicks annually, accounting for up to 50% of all chick deaths in some particularly bad years. &#91;135&#93; &#91;136&#93; Since 1987, the number of breeding pairs in this colony has plummeted by 24%. &#91;136&#93; [Chinstrap penguins](/Chinstrap_penguin) are also in decline, primarily due to a corresponding decrease in their primary food source, [Antarctic krill](/Antarctic_krill). &#91;137&#93; While [Adélie penguins](/Ad%C3%A9lie_penguin) are expected to retain some suitable habitat beyond 2099, projections indicate that one-third of their colonies along the [West Antarctic Peninsula](/West_Antarctic_Peninsula) – representing about 20% of the entire species – will be in decline by 2060. &#91;138&#93; It seems even the most stoic creatures cannot escape the consequences of human inaction.

#### Terrestrial ecosystems

On the [Antarctic](/Antarctica) continent itself, terrestrial life is sparse and hardy, primarily comprising [lichens](/Lichen) (386 known species), [mosses](/Moss) (133 species), [ice algae](/Ice_algae), and [liverworts](/Liverwort) (27 species). These tenacious organisms are predominantly found in the more hospitable coastal areas. &#91;114&#93; In the [Antarctic Peninsula](/Antarctic_Peninsula), for example, green snow algae boast a combined biomass of approximately 1,300&#160;t (2,900,000&#160;lb). &#91;139&#93; As [glaciers](/Glacier) retreat, they expose new land, which is often swiftly colonized by pioneer [lichen](/Lichen) species, eager to stake a claim in the thawing landscape. &#91;140&#93;

The warming of the [Antarctic Peninsula](/Antarctic_Peninsula) has had a paradoxical effect, increasing the growth rates of [mosses](/Moss) four-fold in some areas. &#91;114&#93; On the other hand, in regions of [Antarctica](/Antarctica) that have become drier, despite the overall warming trend, moss populations have deteriorated significantly. &#91;114&#93; The reduction in precipitation in [East Antarctica](/East_Antarctica) has literally changed the color of many green [mosses](/Moss), turning them red or brown as they struggle to cope with drought conditions. The species *Schistidium antarctici* has declined, while the more desiccation-tolerant species like [Bryum pseudotriquetrum](/Bryum_pseudotriquetrum) and [Ceratodon purpureus](/Ceratodon_purpureus) have increased, a subtle but significant shift in the flora. &#91;141&#93; Similarly, [lichens](/Lichen) have exhibited more rapid growth in areas where warming does not interfere with precipitation, such as on [Livingston Island](/Livingston_Island). However, they have declined in places where snowfall has become more intense, burying them more frequently, as observed on the [South Shetland Islands](/South_Shetland_Islands). &#91;114&#93;

Adding another layer of complexity, the [Antarctic ozone hole](/Antarctic_ozone_hole) has led to an increase in [UV-B](/UV-B) radiation reaching the surface. This heightened radiation causes observable damage to living cells, reducing their capacity to [photosynthesize](/Photosynthesis), a fundamental process for life. &#91;142&#93; Moreover, the unfortunate truth is that greater warming also attracts more people to [Antarctica](/Antarctica). The local flora, having never experienced such constant intrusion, is profoundly affected, with even human footprints directly modifying their delicate habitat. &#91;114&#93; One estimate, rather chillingly, suggests that every additional person at an [Antarctica research station](/Antarctica_research_station) on average disturbs an area equivalent to nearly 1,000 [football fields](/Football_field_(area)). &#91;114&#93;

The only native [vascular plants](/Vascular_plant) on continental [Antarctica](/Antarctica) are the [Antarctic hairgrass](/Antarctic_hairgrass) and [Antarctic pearlwort](/Antarctic_pearlwort), both confined to the relatively milder [Antarctic Peninsula](/Antarctic_Peninsula). &#91;142&#93; Increased temperatures have boosted their [photosynthesis](/Photosynthesis) rates, allowing these species to expand their populations and geographical range. &#91;143&#93; However, this localized success comes with a looming threat: other plant species are increasingly likely to spread to [Antarctica](/Antarctica) as the climate continues to warm and as human activity on the continent intensifies, introducing new competition. &#91;142&#93; &#91;126&#93; [Annual bluegrass](/Annual_bluegrass), for instance, already maintains stable populations on the Antarctic islands &#91;114&#93; and is expected to become successfully established in coastal [Antarctica](/Antarctica) around mid-century under scenarios of high warming. &#91;66&#93; Based on seed trait analysis, a concerning 16 other species are considered capable of successfully invading [Antarctica](/Antarctica) in the near future, further altering its unique and fragile terrestrial [ecosystems](/Ecosystem). &#91;114&#93;

### Effects of human development

The allure of [Antarctica](/Antarctica), even as it visibly changes, continues to draw crowds. [Tourism in Antarctica](/Tourism_in_Antarctica) has seen a significant surge since 2020, with a staggering 74,400 tourists arriving in late 2019 and early 2020 alone. &#91;98&#93; &#91;144&#93; This burgeoning interest, coupled with the potential for industrial development and a steady increase in research facilities, places considerable pressure on the continent, threatening its hard-won status as a largely untouched wilderness. &#91;145&#93; Proponents argue that regulated tourism in [Antarctica](/Antarctica) can, paradoxically, foster awareness and encourage the investment and public support necessary to preserve its distinctive environment. &#91;146&#93; However, an unmitigated loss of both land and [sea ice](/Sea_ice) would, quite simply, greatly diminish its unique attractiveness, rendering the very thing tourists come to see a shadow of its former self. &#91;147&#93;

To mitigate these impacts, policy frameworks are in place, aiming to increase [climate-change resilience](/Climate_change_adaptation) through the protection of [ecosystems](/Ecosystem). Ships operating in Antarctic waters are mandated to adhere to the international [Polar Code](/Polar_Code), a comprehensive set of regulations and safety measures. These include rigorous operational training and assessments, strict controls on oil discharge, appropriate sewage disposal protocols, and stringent prevention of pollution by toxic liquids. &#91;148&#93; Furthermore, the [Antarctic Treaty](/Antarctic_Treaty) designates [Antarctic Specially Protected Areas](/Antarctic_Specially_Protected_Area) (ASPA) and [Antarctic Specially Managed Areas](/Antarctic_Specially_Managed_Area) (ASMA) specifically to safeguard its fragile [flora](/Antarctic_flora) and [fauna](/Wildlife_of_Antarctica). &#91;149&#93; Both ASPAs and ASMAs restrict entry, though to varying degrees, with ASPAs representing the highest level of protection. Alarmingly, the designation of new ASPAs has decreased by 84% since the 1980s, despite the rapid escalation in tourism. This creates a worrying imbalance, potentially introducing additional stressors to the natural environment and its unique [ecosystems](/Ecosystem). &#91;142&#93; To alleviate the mounting stress on Antarctic [ecosystems](/Ecosystem) posed by [climate change](/Climate_change) and the exponential increase in tourism, a significant portion of the scientific community advocates for a crucial increase in protected areas like ASPAs, deeming it essential to enhance [Antarctica's](/Antarctica) resilience to rising temperatures. &#91;142&#93;

In a relatively new and unsettling development, researchers from the University of Southampton discovered, since late June 2025, an unexpected increase in surface salinity south of latitude 50°. This shift marks a reversal of decades of freshening tendencies in the region. This increased salinity has, in turn, weakened ocean stratification, paradoxically enabling warmer deep waters to rise and melt [sea ice](/Sea_ice) from beneath. This process has led to the formation of historic polynyas – areas of open water within the ice pack – including the reappearance of the Maud Rise polynya, an area four times the size of Wales, a stark reminder that the [Southern Ocean](/Southern_Ocean) still holds surprises, and not always pleasant ones. &#91;150&#93;

